Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.06,0:00:03.63,ENG,,0,0,0,,- This is the most dangerous problem in mathematics,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.06,0:00:03.63,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是数学界最危险的课题
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.63,0:00:08.05,ENG,,0,0,0,,one that young mathematicians are warned not to waste their time on.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.63,0:00:08.05,CHN,,0,0,0,,前人会告诫年轻的数学家  别把光阴浪费于此
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.05,0:00:09.52,ENG,,0,0,0,,It's a simple conjecture
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.05,0:00:09.52,CHN,,0,0,0,,这个猜想的描述十分简单
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.52,0:00:13.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,that not even the world's best mathematicians have been able to solve.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:09.52,0:00:13.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,却连世界上最聪明的数学家也无法证明
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.33,0:00:16.16,ENG,,0,0,0,,Paul Erdős, a famous mathematician, said,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.33,0:00:16.16,CHN,,0,0,0,,著名数学家Paul Erdős曾说过
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.16,0:00:22.53,Caption,,0,0,0,,{\an8}{\pos(1360,640)}{\fn华文中宋-SC}{\fs60}当今的数学还没有成熟到能解决这种问题
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.16,0:00:22.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,Here's how it works.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:21.16,0:00:22.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,这个猜想是这样的
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.95,0:00:25.29,ENG,,0,0,0,,Pick a number, any number.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.95,0:00:25.29,CHN,,0,0,0,,选个数字  随便选哪个
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.29,0:00:26.23,ENG,,0,0,0,,Seven?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:25.29,0:00:26.23,CHN,,0,0,0,,7{\fsp-30}？
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.23,0:00:27.39,ENG,,0,0,0,,Good choice.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.23,0:00:27.39,CHN,,0,0,0,,好的
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.39,0:00:29.64,ENG,,0,0,0,,Okay, we're gonna apply two rules.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.39,0:00:29.64,CHN,,0,0,0,,我们有两条规则
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.64,0:00:33.21,ENG,,0,0,0,,If the number is odd, we multiply by three and add one.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.64,0:00:33.21,CHN,,0,0,0,,如果这是个奇数 把它乘3加1
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.21,0:00:37.31,ENG,,0,0,0,,So three times seven is 21, plus one is 22.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.21,0:00:37.31,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以7乘3得21  加1得22
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.31,0:00:40.39,ENG,,0,0,0,,If the number is even, we divide by two.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.31,0:00:40.39,CHN,,0,0,0,,如果是个偶数  那就把它除以2
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.39,0:00:43.51,ENG,,0,0,0,,So 22 divided by two is 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.39,0:00:43.51,CHN,,0,0,0,,那么22除以2就得到了11
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.51,0:00:46.22,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, we keep applying these two rules.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:43.51,0:00:46.22,CHN,,0,0,0,,不断重复这两条规则
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.22,0:00:50.75,ENG,,0,0,0,,11 is odd, so we multiply by 3, 33, and add 1, 34.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.22,0:00:50.75,CHN,,0,0,0,,11是奇数  ×3得33  +1得34
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.75,0:00:54.35,ENG,,0,0,0,,Even, divide by two, 17, odd.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.75,0:00:54.35,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是偶数  ÷2得17  是奇数
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.35,0:00:58.00,ENG,,0,0,0,,Multiply by 3, 51, add 1, 52, even.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.35,0:00:58.00,CHN,,0,0,0,,×3是51  +1得52  是偶数
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.00,0:01:00.86,ENG,,0,0,0,,Divide by two, 26, still even.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.00,0:01:00.86,CHN,,0,0,0,,÷2得26  还是偶数
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.86,0:01:03.76,ENG,,0,0,0,,Divide by two, 13, odd.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:00.86,0:01:03.76,CHN,,0,0,0,,÷2得13  是奇数
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.76,0:01:06.97,ENG,,0,0,0,,So we multiply by three, 39, add one, and that's 40,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:03.76,0:01:06.97,CHN,,0,0,0,,于是我们×3得39  再+1得40
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.97,0:01:09.70,ENG,,0,0,0,,which is even, so we divide by two, 20,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.97,0:01:09.70,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是偶数  于是÷2得20
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.70,0:01:13.87,ENG,,0,0,0,,divide by two, 10, divide by two, 5, odd.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.70,0:01:13.87,CHN,,0,0,0,,再÷2得10  再÷2得5  奇数
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.87,0:01:17.10,ENG,,0,0,0,,Multiply by three, 15, add one, 16,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:13.87,0:01:17.10,CHN,,0,0,0,,×3为15  再+1得到16
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.10,0:01:22.10,ENG,,0,0,0,,divide by two that's 8, and then 4, 2, and 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:17.10,0:01:22.10,CHN,,0,0,0,,÷2得到8  一直下去是4, 2, 1
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.30,0:01:26.51,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, 1 is odd, so we multiply by three and add one, which equals 4.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:22.30,0:01:26.51,CHN,,0,0,0,,现在  1是奇数  所以我们把它×3+1得到4
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.51,0:01:29.29,ENG,,0,0,0,,But 4 goes to 2, goes to 1,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.51,0:01:29.29,CHN,,0,0,0,,但4会变为2再变回1
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.29,0:01:33.19,ENG,,0,0,0,,so we're in a loop, and the lowest number is 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:29.29,0:01:33.19,CHN,,0,0,0,,最后就在绕圈子了  最小的数是1
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.19,0:01:35.28,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, the conjecture is this:
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.19,0:01:35.28,CHN,,0,0,0,,这个猜想是
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.28,0:01:38.35,ENG,,0,0,0,,every positive integer, if you apply these rules,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.28,0:01:38.35,CHN,,0,0,0,,对于任意正整数  如果不断重复这两条规则
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.35,0:01:42.77,ENG,,0,0,0,,will eventually end up in the 4, 2, 1 loop.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:38.35,0:01:42.77,CHN,,0,0,0,,最终都会进入 4-2-1 的循环
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.77,0:01:47.47,ENG,,0,0,0,,This is commonly called the Collatz conjecture after German mathematician, Luther Collatz,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:42.77,0:01:47.47,CHN,,0,0,0,,这个猜想常被称为「考拉兹猜想」 得名于德国数学家卢瑟·考拉兹
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.47,0:01:49.93,ENG,,0,0,0,,who may have come up with it in the 1930s.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:47.47,0:01:49.93,CHN,,0,0,0,,提出时间大约是20世纪30年代
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.93,0:01:53.31,ENG,,0,0,0,,But the problem has many origin stories and many names.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.93,0:01:53.31,CHN,,0,0,0,,但这个猜想还被许多人分别独立地发现  因而得名颇多
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.31,0:01:54.44,ENG,,0,0,0,,It's also known as the
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.31,0:01:54.44,CHN,,0,0,0,,它也被称为
Dialogue: 0,0:01:54.44,0:01:55.50,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an5}{\pos(960,730)}{\fs100}{\fsp3}乌拉姆猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.50,0:01:56.70,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an5}{\pos(960,730)}{\fs100}{\fsp3}角谷猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:01:56.70,0:01:57.79,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an5}{\pos(960,730)}{\fs100}{\fsp3}思韦茨猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.79,0:01:59.22,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an5}{\pos(960,730)}{\fs100}{\fsp3}哈塞猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.22,0:02:00.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an5}{\pos(960,730)}{\fs100}{\fsp3}叙拉古猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.27,0:02:02.62,ENG,,0,0,0,,and simply 3N+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.27,0:02:02.62,CHN,,0,0,0,,或者干脆叫3N+1猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.62,0:02:05.55,ENG,,0,0,0,,Why is 3x+1 so famous?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:02.62,0:02:05.55,CHN,,0,0,0,,3X+1 问题为何如此著名
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.55,0:02:09.43,ENG,,0,0,0,,- Among professional mathematicians, maybe it's not famous but infamous,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.55,0:02:09.43,CHN,,0,0,0,,它在职业数学家当中的确很知名{\fsp-8}—{\fsp0}—但是知的是恶名
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.43,0:02:14.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,in the sense that if someone actually admits in public that they're working on it,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.43,0:02:14.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,大家公认  如果谁公开说自己在证明这个猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.15,0:02:15.56,ENG,,0,0,0,,then there's something wrong with them.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:14.15,0:02:15.56,CHN,,0,0,0,,那他肯定有猫病
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.33,0:02:20.48,ENG,,0,0,0,,- The numbers you get by applying 3x+1 are called
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.33,0:02:20.48,CHN,,0,0,0,,通过3x+1过程得到的数被称为
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.48,0:02:26.24,Caption,,0,0,0,,{\an5}{\pos(960,320)}{\fs100}{\fsp3\c&H000000&}冰雹数
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.25,0:02:26.60,ENG,,0,0,0,,because they go up and down like hailstones in a thundercloud,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.25,0:02:26.60,CHN,,0,0,0,,因为它们上上下下  好像雷雨云里的冰雹
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.60,0:02:30.06,ENG,,0,0,0,,but eventually, they all fall down to one,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.60,0:02:30.06,CHN,,0,0,0,,但是它们最终统统都会落到1
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.06,0:02:32.73,ENG,,0,0,0,,or at least we think they do.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.06,0:02:32.73,CHN,,0,0,0,,至少我们现在猜测是这样
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.73,0:02:36.88,ENG,,0,0,0,,You can think of the numbers as representing the height above the ground in meters.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.73,0:02:36.88,CHN,,0,0,0,,你可以把这些数当成海拔高度
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.88,0:02:40.85,ENG,,0,0,0,,So a number like 26 would start 26 meters above the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.88,0:02:40.85,CHN,,0,0,0,,那么26这个数就表示海拔26米
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.85,0:02:45.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,And if you apply 3x+1, it rises up as high as 40 meters.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:40.85,0:02:45.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,让它跑一遍3x+1  它最高会升到40米
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.03,0:02:48.31,ENG,,0,0,0,,And, in total, it takes 10 steps to get to one.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.03,0:02:48.31,CHN,,0,0,0,,总共十步过后 它降到1米
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.31,0:02:51.67,ENG,,0,0,0,,So 10 is called its total stopping time.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.31,0:02:51.67,CHN,,0,0,0,,因此  我们称它的停止用时为10
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.67,0:02:54.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,But take the very next number, 27,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.67,0:02:54.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,而挨着26的数27
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.33,0:02:57.61,ENG,,0,0,0,,and it bounces around all over the place.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.33,0:02:57.61,CHN,,0,0,0,,则一路上窜下跳
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.61,0:03:01.32,ENG,,0,0,0,,In fact, it climbs all the way up to 9,232.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.61,0:03:01.32,CHN,,0,0,0,,它在落到底之前  最高冲到了9232米
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.37,0:03:11.42,ENG,,0,0,0,,As an altitude, that is higher than Mount Everest, before it too falls back to the ground.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.37,0:03:11.42,CHN,,0,0,0,,把它当作高度的话 这比珠穆朗玛峰还高
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.42,0:03:16.42,ENG,,0,0,0,,In total, it takes 111 steps for 27 to get down to one
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.42,0:03:16.42,CHN,,0,0,0,,27这个数总共要111步才能掉到1
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.48,0:03:19.66,ENG,,0,0,0,,and end up in the four, two, one loop.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:16.48,0:03:19.66,CHN,,0,0,0,,然后进入 4-2-1 的循环
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.66,0:03:22.83,ENG,,0,0,0,,The paths that different numbers take vary so widely,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.66,0:03:22.83,CHN,,0,0,0,,即使是离得这么近的数
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.83,0:03:25.12,ENG,,0,0,0,,even numbers right next to each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.83,0:03:25.12,CHN,,0,0,0,,它们的路径也相差甚远
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.12,0:03:29.14,ENG,,0,0,0,,So how do you even start to make progress on this problem?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.12,0:03:29.14,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以  这问题有什么突破口吗
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.14,0:03:31.45,ENG,,0,0,0,,Well, honestly, mathematicians struggled.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.14,0:03:31.45,CHN,,0,0,0,,说实在的  连数学家也难搞
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.45,0:03:32.55,ENG,,0,0,0,,- People just decided that
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.45,0:03:32.55,CHN,,0,0,0,,有些人说
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.55,0:03:37.60,ENG,,0,0,0,,this was something invented by the Soviets to slow down U.S. science,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.55,0:03:37.60,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是苏联人发明的阴谋  用来阻碍美国的科学发展
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.55,0:03:39.23,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an7}{\s1}警惕境外势力打数学牌{\s0}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.60,0:03:39.23,ENG,,0,0,0,,and it was doing a good job at it
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.60,0:03:39.23,CHN,,0,0,0,,而且这“阴谋”真的做到了
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.23,0:03:41.22,ENG,,0,0,0,,'cause everybody's sitting there, twiddling their thumbs
Dialogue: 0,0:03:39.23,0:03:41.22,CHN,,0,0,0,,大把人都在掰着手指头研究这问题
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.22,0:03:46.08,ENG,,0,0,0,,and making no progress on this trivial thing that you can tell a school of children.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.22,0:03:46.08,CHN,,0,0,0,,但在这个简单到小学生都听得懂的问题上  他们毫无进展
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.08,0:03:49.81,ENG,,0,0,0,,- Jeffrey Lagarias is the world authority on 3x+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.08,0:03:49.81,CHN,,0,0,0,,在世界范围内  Jeffrey Lagarias是研究3x+1问题的权威
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.81,0:03:53.44,ENG,,0,0,0,,- The first time I met him I was a senior in college,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.81,0:03:53.44,CHN,,0,0,0,,我读大四的时候第一次在大学里遇到他
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.44,0:03:55.98,ENG,,0,0,0,,and he pulled me aside and he said,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:53.44,0:03:55.98,CHN,,0,0,0,,他把我拉到一边  他说
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.98,0:03:58.78,ENG,,0,0,0,,"Don't do this. Don't work on this problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.98,0:03:58.78,CHN,,0,0,0,,快跑  别折腾这玩意
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.78,0:04:00.94,ENG,,0,0,0,,If you want to have a career,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.78,0:04:00.94,CHN,,0,0,0,,如果你不想被同行鄙视  不想丢饭碗
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.94,0:04:04.98,ENG,,0,0,0,,do not start spending time writing about this
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.98,0:04:07.23,ENG,,0,0,0,,or publishing any papers about this.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:00.94,0:04:07.23,CHN,,0,0,0,,就别在这玩意上面浪费时间来写论文  发论文
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.23,0:04:10.37,ENG,,0,0,0,,Do real math for a while to establish yourself."
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.23,0:04:10.37,CHN,,0,0,0,,花点时间去研究真正的数学  来打好你的基础
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.37,0:04:12.65,ENG,,0,0,0,,- Alex Kontorovich didn't listen.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:10.37,0:04:12.65,CHN,,0,0,0,,Alex Kontorovich 并不听话
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.65,0:04:16.89,ENG,,0,0,0,,He and Yakov Sinai looked at the paths of the hailstone numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.65,0:04:16.89,CHN,,0,0,0,,他和 Yakov Sinai 观察了这些冰雹数的走势
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.89,0:04:18.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,Were there any patterns?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.89,0:04:18.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,看看有没有什么规律
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.33,0:04:20.41,ENG,,0,0,0,,But obviously all of them ended up at one.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.33,0:04:20.41,CHN,,0,0,0,,显然这些数最后都变成了1
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.42,0:04:23.74,ENG,,0,0,0,,But what about the paths they take to get there?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:20.42,0:04:23.74,CHN,,0,0,0,,那么  变到1所走的路径呢
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.74,0:04:26.61,ENG,,0,0,0,,The pattern is randomness.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:23.74,0:04:26.61,CHN,,0,0,0,,完全随机
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.61,0:04:30.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,Here is the sequence of a large number chosen at random.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.61,0:04:30.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,我们任意选一个超大的数  图里展示了它的变化过程
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.01,0:04:32.05,ENG,,0,0,0,,The graph peaks and then drop so low
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.01,0:04:32.05,CHN,,0,0,0,,图像先冲到一个高峰  再掉得超低
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.05,0:04:34.72,ENG,,0,0,0,,that you can't really see what's happening at this scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.05,0:04:34.72,CHN,,0,0,0,,低到在这个比例下根本看不出走势
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.72,0:04:36.32,ENG,,0,0,0,,But if you take the logarithm,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:34.72,0:04:36.32,CHN,,0,0,0,,但是如果用对数比例
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.32,0:04:40.02,ENG,,0,0,0,,you find this wiggly graph with a downward trend.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.32,0:04:40.02,CHN,,0,0,0,,你会看到这个一路蠕动下降的图
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.02,0:04:42.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,It looks like the stock market on a bad day.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.02,0:04:42.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,就像你血本无归的基金
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.95,0:04:45.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,And this is no coincidence.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.95,0:04:45.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,而且这不是巧合
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.01,0:04:48.56,ENG,,0,0,0,,Both are examples of geometric Brownian motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.01,0:04:48.56,CHN,,0,0,0,,二者都是几何布朗运动的例子
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.56,0:04:53.91,ENG,,0,0,0,,That means if you take the log and remove the linear trend, the fluctuations are random.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.56,0:04:53.91,CHN,,0,0,0,,意思是说 如果把它取对数之后放平  这些波动就是随机的了
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.91,0:04:55.71,ENG,,0,0,0,,It's like flipping a coin each step.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.91,0:04:55.71,CHN,,0,0,0,,就像是每一步都抛硬币
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.71,0:04:58.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,If the coin is heads, the line goes up,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.71,0:04:58.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,正面的话折线往上走
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.03,0:05:00.07,ENG,,0,0,0,,tails, it goes down.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.03,0:05:00.07,CHN,,0,0,0,,反面就往下走
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.07,0:05:03.91,ENG,,0,0,0,,3x+1 is just like the random wiggles of the stock market.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:00.07,0:05:03.91,CHN,,0,0,0,,3x+1 就好像是股市的波动
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.91,0:05:07.32,ENG,,0,0,0,,Over long-enough periods, the stock market tends to trend upwards,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.91,0:05:07.32,CHN,,0,0,0,,只要时间足够长 （美国）股市趋向于上涨
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.32,0:05:09.88,ENG,,0,0,0,,while 3x+1 trends down.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.32,0:05:09.88,CHN,,0,0,0,,而 3x+1 趋向于下降
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.74,0:05:12.47,ENG,,0,0,0,,Another way to analyze 3x+1
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.74,0:05:12.47,CHN,,0,0,0,,另一种分析 3x+1 的方式
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.47,0:05:16.37,ENG,,0,0,0,,is by looking at the leading digit of each number in a sequence.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.47,0:05:16.37,CHN,,0,0,0,,是研究 3x+1 数列里各项的首位
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.37,0:05:20.41,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}Here are the hailstone numbers starting with three as the seed.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.37,0:05:20.41,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}这里我们选取3作为初值  看看它的冰雹数列
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.41,0:05:22.72,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}And we can count up how many numbers start with a one,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.41,0:05:22.72,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}然后统计有几个数的首位是1
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.72,0:05:24.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}how many start with a two,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.72,0:05:24.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}几个数的首位是2
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.27,0:05:28.06,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}how many start with a three, and so on to make a histogram.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:24.27,0:05:28.06,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}几个数的首位是3  以此类推  做出直方图
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.06,0:05:32.99,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}We can do the same thing for the sequence that starts with four, and that's a short one,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.06,0:05:32.99,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}同样的  我们看始于4的数列  这就挺短的了
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.99,0:05:35.82,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}and for the sequences that start with five
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.99,0:05:35.82,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}接着看始于5的…
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.82,0:05:36.66,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}six,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.82,0:05:36.66,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}接着看始于5的… 6的…
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.66,0:05:38.19,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}and seven.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:36.66,0:05:38.19,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}接着看始于5的… 6的… 7的
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.19,0:05:39.97,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}Again, for each sequence,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.19,0:05:39.97,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}对于各个冰雹数列
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.97,0:05:43.86,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}we're just counting up how many numbers start with each digit, 1 through 9,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.97,0:05:43.86,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}按照首位是1-9来分别清点
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.86,0:05:46.78,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}and adding that to our histogram.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.86,0:05:46.78,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}然后加到直方图里
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.78,0:05:49.64,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}If you keep doing this for more and more numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.78,0:05:49.64,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}只要统计的数越来越多
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.64,0:05:53.69,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}eventually the histogram settles into a stable pattern.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.64,0:05:53.69,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}直方图最终会趋向于稳定的比例
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.69,0:05:56.07,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}For the first billion sequences,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.69,0:05:56.07,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}对于前十亿项
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.07,0:06:00.70,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}you'll find one is by far the most common leading digit.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:56.07,0:06:00.70,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}你会发现1是最常作为首位的数码
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.70,0:06:04.20,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}30% of all numbers start with one,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.70,0:06:04.20,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}30%的数以1打头
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.20,0:06:09.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}around 17.5% start with two, 12% start with three,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:04.20,0:06:09.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}17.5%以2打头  12%以3打头
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.03,0:06:11.71,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}and the frequency decreases for higher digits.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.03,0:06:11.71,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}随着首位递增  其出现频率会递减
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.71,0:06:15.67,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}Fewer than 5% of all the numbers start with nine.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.71,0:06:15.67,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}以9打头的数只占了不到5%
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.67,0:06:19.25,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, this pattern is not unique to 3x+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.67,0:06:19.25,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,这个规律并非是3x+1独有的
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.25,0:06:21.67,ENG,,0,0,0,,It actually comes up everywhere,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.25,0:06:21.67,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,它其实会出现在许多领域
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.67,0:06:23.63,ENG,,0,0,0,,from the populations of countries,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.67,0:06:22.11,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,从国家人口数
Dialogue: 0,0:06:22.11,0:06:23.63,CHN,,0,0,0,,从国家人口数
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.63,0:06:25.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,to the value of companies,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.63,0:06:25.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,到公司价值
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.33,0:06:26.88,ENG,,0,0,0,,all the physical constants
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.33,0:06:26.88,CHN,,0,0,0,,物理常数
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.88,0:06:30.07,ENG,,0,0,0,,and the Fibonacci numbers, just to name a few.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.88,0:06:30.07,CHN,,0,0,0,,乃至斐波那契数  不胜枚举
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.07,0:06:34.20,ENG,,0,0,0,,The distribution is known as Benford's law,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.07,0:06:34.20,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,这个分布被称为「本福特   定律{\fsp-30}」
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.20,0:06:36.98,ENG,,0,0,0,,and it is even used to detect fraud.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.20,0:06:36.98,CHN,,0,0,0,,它甚至能检测财务欺诈
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.98,0:06:39.77,ENG,,0,0,0,,If all the numbers on your income tax forms obey Benford's law,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.98,0:06:39.77,CHN,,0,0,0,,如果你在税务申报表上的所有数值都符合这个定律
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.77,0:06:42.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,then, well, you're probably being honest.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.77,0:06:42.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,那你应该是诚实的
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.03,0:06:44.72,ENG,,0,0,0,,If not, you may be hiding something.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.03,0:06:44.72,CHN,,0,0,0,,没有的话  你是不是想搞事情
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.72,0:06:48.07,ENG,,0,0,0,,In elections, Benford's law can be used to spot irregularities,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.72,0:06:48.07,CHN,,0,0,0,,在选举中  本福特定律也能用来发现异常
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.07,0:06:50.42,ENG,,0,0,0,,though you have to apply it correctly.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.07,0:06:50.42,CHN,,0,0,0,,当然你得用对
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.42,0:06:55.20,ENG,,0,0,0,,Benford's law works best when the numbers involved span several orders of magnitude
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.42,0:06:55.20,CHN,,0,0,0,,这一定律最适合用于  数据范围跨越好几个数量级的情况
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.20,0:06:57.82,ENG,,0,0,0,,as they do for 3x+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.20,0:06:57.82,CHN,,0,0,0,,就如 3x+1 一样
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.82,0:06:59.99,ENG,,0,0,0,,But Benford's law can't tell us
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.82,0:06:59.99,CHN,,0,0,0,,不过它并不能告诉我们
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.99,0:07:04.80,ENG,,0,0,0,,whether all numbers will end up in the four, two, one loop or not.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.99,0:07:04.80,CHN,,0,0,0,,是不是所有数字都会落入 4-2-1 循环
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.80,0:07:07.97,ENG,,0,0,0,,For that, we need a different sort of analysis.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.80,0:07:07.97,CHN,,0,0,0,,为此  我们需要用其他方法来分析
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.97,0:07:10.13,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, at first glance, it seems strange that
Dialogue: 0,0:07:10.13,0:07:13.93,ENG,,0,0,0,,when you apply 3x+1, all numbers should end up at one.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.97,0:07:13.93,CHN,,0,0,0,,乍一看  任意数字代进3x+1最终都得到1是蛮奇怪的
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.93,0:07:18.81,ENG,,0,0,0,,I mean, consider that there are the same number of odd and even numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.93,0:07:18.81,CHN,,0,0,0,,我的意思是 考虑到奇数和偶数是一样多的
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.81,0:07:21.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,but odd numbers are more than tripled,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:18.81,0:07:21.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,但奇数不止翻了两倍
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.33,0:07:24.40,ENG,,0,0,0,,while even numbers are only cut in half.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.33,0:07:24.40,CHN,,0,0,0,,而偶数只减少了一半
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.40,0:07:29.40,ENG,,0,0,0,,Therefore, it seems like every sequence on average should grow, not shrink.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.40,0:07:29.40,CHN,,0,0,0,,因此  平均来看  数列应该会趋向上升而非下降
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.40,0:07:30.67,ENG,,0,0,0,,But here's the catch.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.40,0:07:30.67,CHN,,0,0,0,,但这就是问题所在
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.67,0:07:33.88,ENG,,0,0,0,,Every time you multiply an odd number by 3 and then add 1,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.67,0:07:33.88,CHN,,0,0,0,,每当一个奇数×3+1
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.88,0:07:36.76,ENG,,0,0,0,,it will always become an even number,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.88,0:07:36.76,CHN,,0,0,0,,它一定会变成偶数
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.76,0:07:40.00,ENG,,0,0,0,,and that means the next step is to divide by 2.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.76,0:07:40.00,CHN,,0,0,0,,下一步它就会÷2
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.00,0:07:43.55,ENG,,0,0,0,,So odd numbers are not actually tripled by 3x+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.00,0:07:43.55,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以奇数实际上不会因为3x+1变成原来的三倍
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.55,0:07:46.69,ENG,,0,0,0,,They're increased by a factor of about three over two.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.55,0:07:46.69,CHN,,0,0,0,,它们会增长到原来的3/2
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.69,0:07:47.96,ENG,,0,0,0,,I'm neglecting the plus one
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.69,0:07:47.96,CHN,,0,0,0,,+1可以忽略
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.96,0:07:51.17,ENG,,0,0,0,,because it's insignificant for large numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.96,0:07:51.17,CHN,,0,0,0,,因为它对于大数是微不足道的
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.17,0:07:57.16,ENG,,0,0,0,,And 3/2 is actually the most an odd number can grow in one step.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.17,0:07:57.16,CHN,,0,0,0,,而且 3/2 倍是奇数在一步之内能增长的最大值
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.16,0:08:01.43,ENG,,0,0,0,,Think of the path from one odd number in a sequence to the next odd number.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.16,0:08:01.43,CHN,,0,0,0,,考虑3x+1数列中  由所有奇数组成的变化路径
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.43,0:08:05.29,ENG,,0,0,0,,After multiplying by 3 and adding 1, you have an even number.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.43,0:08:05.29,CHN,,0,0,0,,奇数在×3+1之后  你就得到了偶数
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.29,0:08:10.22,ENG,,0,0,0,,And 50% of the time, dividing by 2 brings you back to an odd number.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.29,0:08:10.22,CHN,,0,0,0,,有50%的可能  ÷2就能变回奇数
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.22,0:08:14.64,ENG,,0,0,0,,But 1/4 of the time, you can divide by 4 before you get to the next odd number.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.22,0:08:14.64,CHN,,0,0,0,,但还有1/4的可能  要÷4才会变回奇数
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.64,0:08:21.21,ENG,,0,0,0,,So, for 1/4 of numbers, the next one in the sequence will be 3/4 of its initial value.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.64,0:08:21.21,CHN,,0,0,0,,这种情况下  下面的红圈里的数会是上面的3/4
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.21,0:08:25.14,ENG,,0,0,0,,An 1/8 the time, you can divide by 8 before getting to the next odd number,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.21,0:08:25.14,CHN,,0,0,0,,有1/8的可能  要÷8才会得到下一个奇数
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.14,0:08:29.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,and 1/16 of the time, you can divide by 16 and so on.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.14,0:08:29.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,有1/16的可能  要÷16才行  以此类推
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.27,0:08:32.13,ENG,,0,0,0,,If you take the geometric mean, you find
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.27,0:08:32.13,CHN,,0,0,0,,算算几何平均数  可以发现
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.13,0:08:35.68,ENG,,0,0,0,,on average, to get from one odd number to the next one,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.68,0:08:39.91,ENG,,0,0,0,,you multiply by 3/4, which is less than one.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.13,0:08:39.91,CHN,,0,0,0,,序列里的后一个奇数平均是前一个奇数的3/4倍  也就是平均会变小
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.91,0:08:45.92,ENG,,0,0,0,,So statistically speaking, 3x+1 sequences are more likely to shrink than grow.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.91,0:08:45.92,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以从统计学上讲  3x+1数列更倾向于收缩  而非增长
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.92,0:08:48.35,ENG,,0,0,0,,Take 341 for example,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.92,0:08:48.35,CHN,,0,0,0,,用341做例子
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.35,0:08:52.25,ENG,,0,0,0,,multiply by three and add one, you get 1,024,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:48.35,0:08:52.25,CHN,,0,0,0,,×3+1得到1024
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.25,0:08:54.34,ENG,,0,0,0,,which you can divide by two
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.25,0:08:54.34,CHN,,0,0,0,,你可以把它÷2
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.34,0:08:58.42,ENG,,0,0,0,,and then divide by two again, and again, and again, and again,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.34,0:08:58.42,CHN,,0,0,0,,再÷2  再÷2  ÷2  ÷2…
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.42,0:09:01.74,ENG,,0,0,0,,10 times in total until you're down to one.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.42,0:09:01.74,CHN,,0,0,0,,10步后会到达1
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.62,0:09:06.06,ENG,,0,0,0,,One way to visualize these paths of numbers in 3x+1
Dialogue: 0,0:09:02.62,0:09:06.06,CHN,,0,0,0,,有种方法能形象地描述3x+1数列的路径
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.06,0:09:10.36,ENG,,0,0,0,,is simply to show how each number connects to the next one in its sequence.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.06,0:09:10.36,CHN,,0,0,0,,就是把序列中每个相邻的数画条边连接
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.36,0:09:13.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,This is called a directed graph.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.36,0:09:13.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,这就是所谓的「有向图{\fsp-30}」
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.15,0:09:18.17,ENG,,0,0,0,,It looks like a tree or a series of little streams that flow into each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.15,0:09:18.17,CHN,,0,0,0,,它看起来像一棵树  或者是一大片逐渐汇聚的溪流
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.17,0:09:24.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,If the conjecture is true, it means that every single number is connected to this graph.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.17,0:09:24.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,如果这个猜想成立  那就意味着所有的正整数都会连在这个图里
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.15,0:09:27.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,Every tiny stream all the way out to infinity
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.15,0:09:27.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,每条从1一直上溯至无穷的小溪流
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.54,0:09:32.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,eventually flows into the massive river of four, two, one.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.54,0:09:32.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,最终都会汇入 4-2-1 的洪流
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.00,0:09:39.56,ENG,,0,0,0,,Some mathematicians have modified this visualization by rotating the graph at each number;
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.00,0:09:39.56,CHN,,0,0,0,,有些数学家换了种方法来描绘{\fsp-7}—{\r}—把图里的每个数字转个角度
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.56,0:09:41.40,ENG,,0,0,0,,anticlockwise if it's an odd number,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.56,0:09:41.40,CHN,,0,0,0,,如果是奇数  就逆时针转
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.40,0:09:43.81,ENG,,0,0,0,,and clockwise if it's even.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.40,0:09:43.81,CHN,,0,0,0,,是偶数  就顺时针转
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.81,0:09:49.86,ENG,,0,0,0,,And then you end up with a structure that looks like a coral or seaweed.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:43.81,0:09:49.86,CHN,,0,0,0,,最后你会得到一个看起来像珊瑚或者海草的结构
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.86,0:09:53.46,ENG,,0,0,0,,And by adjusting the degree of rotation for odd and even numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.86,0:09:53.46,CHN,,0,0,0,,通过改变奇数和偶数旋转的角度
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.46,0:09:57.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,you can create these beautiful, organic-looking shapes.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:53.46,0:09:57.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,你可以创造出这些美丽的有机形状
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.90,0:10:01.89,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, there are two ways the conjecture could be false.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.90,0:10:01.89,CHN,,0,0,0,,要想推翻这个猜想  有两种方式
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.89,0:10:04.32,ENG,,0,0,0,,There could be a number somewhere, some seed,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.32,0:10:08.85,ENG,,0,0,0,,that starts a sequence of numbers that grows to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.89,0:10:08.85,CHN,,0,0,0,,可能有某个数的3x+1数列会一直增长到无穷
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.85,0:10:14.71,ENG,,0,0,0,,For whatever reason, it doesn't obey the same numerical gravity as all of the other numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:08.85,0:10:14.71,CHN,,0,0,0,,它出于某种原因  不会跟其他数一样落到1
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.71,0:10:20.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,Another possibility is there exists a sequence of numbers that forms a closed loop.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:14.71,0:10:20.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,另一种可能是  存在一批会形成闭环的数
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.53,0:10:25.23,ENG,,0,0,0,,All the numbers in this loop would be unconnected to the main graph.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.53,0:10:25.23,CHN,,0,0,0,,这个环中的所有数字跟主图不联通
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.23,0:10:30.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,But thus far, no loop or sequence that shoots off to infinity has been found.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.23,0:10:30.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,但是目前为止  暂时没人找到有环或者能增长到无穷大的数列
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.53,0:10:34.57,ENG,,0,0,0,,And not for lack of trying, mathematicians have tested by brute force
Dialogue: 0,0:10:30.53,0:10:34.57,CHN,,0,0,0,,数学家们可不是没试过  他们已经穷举了
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.57,0:10:37.16,ENG,,0,0,0,,every single number up to 2^68.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:34.57,0:10:37.16,CHN,,0,0,0,,2的68次方以内的所有数
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.16,0:10:49.06,ENG,,0,0,0,,That's 295,147,905,179,352,825,856 numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.16,0:10:49.06,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是2垓9514京7905兆1793亿5282万5856个数
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.06,0:10:52.65,ENG,,0,0,0,,We know, for certain, that every single one of those numbers
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.65,0:10:55.31,ENG,,0,0,0,,eventually comes back down to one.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.06,0:10:55.31,CHN,,0,0,0,,我们能确定  这里面的任何一个数  最后都会落到1
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.31,0:10:58.64,ENG,,0,0,0,,We have tested nearly 300 quintillion numbers,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:55.31,0:10:58.64,CHN,,0,0,0,,我们测试了接近3万亿亿个数
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.64,0:11:01.56,ENG,,0,0,0,,and none of them disproves the conjecture.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.64,0:11:01.56,CHN,,0,0,0,,没有一个反例
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.56,0:11:03.46,ENG,,0,0,0,,In fact, given this information,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:01.56,0:11:03.46,CHN,,0,0,0,,事实上  依靠这些信息
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.46,0:11:06.94,ENG,,0,0,0,,mathematicians calculate that any loop other than 4, 2, 1
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.46,0:11:06.94,CHN,,0,0,0,,数学家得出  如果存在4-2-1以外的循环
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.94,0:11:11.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,must be at least 186 billion numbers long.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:06.94,0:11:11.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,其至少应包含1860亿个数
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.53,0:11:14.81,ENG,,0,0,0,,So, it seems pretty likely that the conjecture is true,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:11.53,0:11:14.81,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以  看起来这个猜想很像是成立的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.81,0:11:16.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,but this doesn't prove it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:14.81,0:11:16.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,但这并不能证明它
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.95,0:11:19.48,ENG,,0,0,0,,One way mathematicians have attempted to prove it
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.95,0:11:19.48,CHN,,0,0,0,,数学家尝试证明它的一种方法
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.48,0:11:21.72,ENG,,0,0,0,,is by making a scatterplot,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.48,0:11:21.72,CHN,,0,0,0,,是绘制散点图
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.72,0:11:23.91,ENG,,0,0,0,,with all the seed numbers on the x-axis
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.72,0:11:23.91,CHN,,0,0,0,,数列首项在X轴上
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.91,0:11:27.10,ENG,,0,0,0,,and a number from each seeds sequence on the y-axis.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.91,0:11:27.10,CHN,,0,0,0,,数列中产生的数在Y轴上
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.10,0:11:30.89,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, if you can show that in every 3x+1 sequence
Dialogue: 0,0:11:27.10,0:11:30.89,CHN,,0,0,0,,现在  如果能证明每个3x+1数列中
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.89,0:11:34.20,ENG,,0,0,0,,there is a number that is smaller than the original seed,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.89,0:11:34.20,CHN,,0,0,0,,都存在某项小于数列首项
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.20,0:11:36.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,well then you have proven the Collatz conjecture.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.20,0:11:36.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,那就能证明考拉兹猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.95,0:11:38.71,ENG,,0,0,0,,Because whatever number you pick,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:36.95,0:11:38.71,CHN,,0,0,0,,因为无论你选择什么数
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.71,0:11:41.29,ENG,,0,0,0,,you know it will at some point get smaller,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:38.71,0:11:41.29,CHN,,0,0,0,,你都知道它的数列中会有某项更小的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.29,0:11:44.60,ENG,,0,0,0,,and that smaller number as a seed also gets smaller,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:41.29,0:11:44.60,CHN,,0,0,0,,而这个更小的项能继续变得更小
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.60,0:11:46.83,ENG,,0,0,0,,and so on down to 1,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.60,0:11:46.83,CHN,,0,0,0,,以此类推直至落到 1
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.83,0:11:53.04,ENG,,0,0,0,,meaning the only way any sequence can end is in the 4, 2, 1 loop.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.83,0:11:53.04,CHN,,0,0,0,,意味着所有数列都会以 4-2-1 循环结尾
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.04,0:11:56.12,ENG,,0,0,0,,This has not yet been shown.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:53.04,0:11:56.12,CHN,,0,0,0,,这还没有被证明
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.12,0:12:00.76,ENG,,0,0,0,,But, in 1976, Riho Terras was able to show that
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.12,0:12:00.76,CHN,,0,0,0,,但在1976年  Riho Terras证明了
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.76,0:12:05.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,almost all Collatz sequences reach a point below their initial value.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.76,0:12:05.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,「几乎所有」考拉兹数列都存在小于其初值的数
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.54,0:12:12.37,ENG,,0,0,0,,In 1979, this limit was reduced with almost all numbers going to less than X^0.869.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:05.54,0:12:12.37,CHN,,0,0,0,,1979年  上界缩小至「几乎所有」x 的数列都有数小于 x 的0.869次方
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.37,0:12:19.42,ENG,,0,0,0,,And then in 1994, it was further lowered to less than X^0.7925.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.37,0:12:19.42,CHN,,0,0,0,,1994年  上界进一步缩小至 x 的0.7925次方
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.42,0:12:24.72,ENG,,0,0,0,,In this case, the term almost all numbers has a technical mathematical definition.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:19.42,0:12:24.72,CHN,,0,0,0,,术语「几乎所有数」 是数学专门的定义
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.72,0:12:28.77,ENG,,0,0,0,,It means that as the numbers you're looking at go to infinity,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.72,0:12:28.77,CHN,,0,0,0,,它的意思是  只要你要研究的数会一直趋向到无穷
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.77,0:12:32.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,the fraction that end up under the curve goes to one.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.77,0:12:32.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,其比例会渐近趋向于1
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.76,0:12:35.18,ENG,,0,0,0,,Then in 2019,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.76,0:12:35.18,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,2019年
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.18,0:12:37.26,ENG,,0,0,0,,one of the world's greatest living mathematicians,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.18,0:12:35.27,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,目前在世的最伟大的数学家之一
Dialogue: 0,0:12:35.27,0:12:37.26,CHN,,0,0,0,,目前在世的最伟大的数学家之一
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.26,0:12:38.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,Terry Tao,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.26,0:12:38.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,陶哲轩
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.27,0:12:43.30,ENG,,0,0,0,,was able to show 3x+1 obeys even stricter criteria.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:38.27,0:12:43.30,CHN,,0,0,0,,证明了3x+1数列还可以满足更严格的条件
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.30,0:12:43.65,ENG,,0,0,0,,He showed almost all numbers will end up smaller than any arbitrary function f(x)
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.30,0:12:43.65,CHN,,0,0,0,,他证明了  几乎所有数列的归宿  都会小于任意函数f(x)
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.65,0:12:49.81,ENG,,0,0,0,,He showed almost all numbers will end up smaller than any arbitrary function f(x)
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.65,0:12:49.81,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,他证明了  几乎所有数列的归宿  都会小于任意函数f(x)
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.81,0:12:54.22,ENG,,0,0,0,,so long as that function goes to infinity as x goes to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:49.81,0:12:54.22,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,只要当x增长到无穷时  函数会随着增长到无穷
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.22,0:12:57.50,ENG,,0,0,0,,But the function can rise as slowly as you like.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.22,0:12:57.50,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,但这个函数的增长速度可以任意慢
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.50,0:13:02.50,ENG,,0,0,0,,So, log x is an example, or log log log x works too,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.50,0:13:02.50,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,这个函数可以是 log x   也可以是 log log log x
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.53,0:13:04.96,ENG,,0,0,0,,or log log log log x.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.53,0:13:04.96,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,或是 log log log log x
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.96,0:13:09.02,ENG,,0,0,0,,What this means is, for almost all numbers, you can guarantee
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.96,0:13:09.02,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,这个结果的含义是  对几乎所有数  你都可以保证
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.02,0:13:13.99,ENG,,0,0,0,,that there is an arbitrarily small number somewhere in its sequence.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.02,0:13:13.99,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,其数列中有一个比它任意小的数
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.99,0:13:16.67,ENG,,0,0,0,,In a public talk he gave in 2020, Terry Tao said,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.99,0:13:16.67,CHNObq,,0,0,0,,2020年  陶哲轩在一次公开演讲中说
Dialogue: 0,0:13:16.66,0:13:22.69,Caption,,0,0,0,,{\c&H000000&}{\an5}{\fs72}\N\N这个结果距离解答考拉兹猜想只差最后的关键一步了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.80,0:13:27.32,ENG,,0,0,0,,This is an impressive result, but it's still not a proof.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.80,0:13:27.32,CHN,,0,0,0,,这是个令人赞叹的结果  但依然不是证明
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.32,0:13:30.44,ENG,,0,0,0,,So why can't we prove the conjecture true?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:27.32,0:13:30.44,CHN,,0,0,0,,所以我们为什么证明不了猜想成立呢
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.44,0:13:33.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,Could it be because it's not true?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.44,0:13:33.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,有没有可能因为这是个假命题
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.01,0:13:34.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,I mean, everyone is trying to prove it true,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.01,0:13:34.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,我的意思是  每个人都在试图证真
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.90,0:13:38.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,which means almost no one is looking for counterexamples.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:34.90,0:13:38.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,换言之  几乎没有人在找反例
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.54,0:13:40.97,ENG,,0,0,0,,- It had happened to me just two years ago,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.54,0:13:40.97,CHN,,0,0,0,,我两年前就碰到过
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.97,0:13:42.70,ENG,,0,0,0,,where there was something I was trying to prove,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:42.70,0:13:45.64,ENG,,0,0,0,,that I was trying for three years to prove,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:40.97,0:13:45.64,CHN,,0,0,0,,那时我正在我证明一个  我尝试了三年的课题
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.52,0:13:48.94,ENG,,0,0,0,,and I couldn't get it to work.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.52,0:13:48.94,CHN,,0,0,0,,但我就是没法证明其正确性
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.94,0:13:50.37,ENG,,0,0,0,,And then I found a counterexample,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.94,0:13:50.37,CHN,,0,0,0,,结果我找到了个反例
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.37,0:13:52.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,and then I realized what the correct statement should have been.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.37,0:13:52.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,然后我意识到了正确的命题应该是怎样的
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.90,0:13:55.28,ENG,,0,0,0,,And then a month later, I proved the correct statement.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.90,0:13:55.28,CHN,,0,0,0,,一个月后  我证明了那个正确的命题
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.28,0:13:57.13,ENG,,0,0,0,,Maybe we should be spending more energy
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.13,0:13:59.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,looking for counterexamples than we're currently spending.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:55.28,0:13:59.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,或许我们研究这些问题时  应该把更多精力放在寻找反例上
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.90,0:14:05.41,ENG,,0,0,0,,- I mean, remember how the number 27 grows all the way to 9,232?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.90,0:14:05.41,CHN,,0,0,0,,还记得27是如何增长到9232的吗
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.41,0:14:09.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}Here is a plot of seed numbers up to 10,000,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.41,0:14:09.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}这个散点图包含了一万以下的所有初值
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.03,0:14:13.77,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}with the largest number reached for each seed plotted on the y-axis.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.03,0:14:13.77,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}并在Y方向上标出了其3x+1数列中的最大值
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.77,0:14:16.06,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}The y-axis stops at a 100,000,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.77,0:14:16.06,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}Y轴只标记到了十万
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.06,0:14:19.21,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}but not all numbers can be shown at this scale.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.06,0:14:19.21,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}图中并没有将所有的最值都囊括在内
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.21,0:14:25.50,ENG,,0,0,0,,{\an8}The seed 9,663, for example, climbs as high as 27 million.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.21,0:14:25.50,CHN,,0,0,0,,{\an8}比如说  初值为9663时  其最值会攀升至2700万
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.09,0:14:31.32,ENG,,0,0,0,,And as yet, no one has proven why a number couldn't just shoot off to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:26.09,0:14:31.32,CHN,,0,0,0,,目前为止  没有人证明  为什么没有哪个初值会发散
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.32,0:14:34.48,ENG,,0,0,0,,And it would take only one to disprove the conjecture,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.32,0:14:34.48,CHN,,0,0,0,,只要有一个反例  就能证伪这个猜想
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.46,0:14:39.98,ENG,,0,0,0,,or some set of numbers could be part of a loop not connected to the main graph.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:35.46,0:14:39.98,CHN,,0,0,0,,或者存在某些数会形成与主图不相连的循环
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.98,0:14:44.29,ENG,,0,0,0,,As far as we know, there is only one loop: 4, 2, 1.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.98,0:14:44.29,CHN,,0,0,0,,尽管我们现在只知道一个循环：4-2-1
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.29,0:14:48.41,ENG,,0,0,0,,But something strange happens if you include negative numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.29,0:14:48.41,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.41,0:14:51.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,Applying the same 3x+1 rules as before,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.41,0:14:51.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.95,0:14:54.80,ENG,,0,0,0,,there is not one loop, not two loops,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:51.95,0:14:54.80,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.80,0:14:58.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,but three independent loops of numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.80,0:14:58.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.15,0:15:03.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,And they start at low values like -17 and -5.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.15,0:15:03.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.29,0:15:07.43,ENG,,0,0,0,,Why should there be disconnected loops on the negative side of the number line,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.29,0:15:07.43,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.43,0:15:10.05,ENG,,0,0,0,,but not on the positive side?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.43,0:15:10.05,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.05,0:15:13.45,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, one of the most convincing pieces of evidence supporting the conjecture is
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.05,0:15:13.45,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.45,0:15:15.73,ENG,,0,0,0,,Terry Tao's proof that almost all numbers
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.45,0:15:15.73,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.73,0:15:19.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,have a number in their sequence that is arbitrarily small.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.73,0:15:19.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.15,0:15:22.87,ENG,,0,0,0,,But proving that almost all numbers obey this criteria
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.15,0:15:22.87,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.87,0:15:26.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,isn't the same thing as proving that all numbers do.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.87,0:15:26.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.52,0:15:31.94,ENG,,0,0,0,,How many numbers between one and 100 are perfect squares?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.52,0:15:31.94,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.94,0:15:33.87,ENG,,0,0,0,,The answer is 10.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.94,0:15:33.87,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.87,0:15:37.94,ENG,,0,0,0,,So, 10% of numbers up to 100 are perfect squares.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.87,0:15:37.94,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.94,0:15:41.84,ENG,,0,0,0,,How many numbers between one and 1,000 are perfect squares?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.94,0:15:41.84,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.84,0:15:43.93,ENG,,0,0,0,,The answer is 31.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.84,0:15:43.93,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.93,0:15:48.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,So only 3.1% of the numbers up to 1,000 are perfect squares.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.93,0:15:48.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.53,0:15:52.69,ENG,,0,0,0,,And the higher you go, the smaller this percentage becomes,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.53,0:15:52.69,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.69,0:15:54.80,ENG,,0,0,0,,such that in the limit, you could say
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.69,0:15:54.80,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.80,0:15:58.12,ENG,,0,0,0,,almost all numbers are not perfect squares.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:54.80,0:15:58.12,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.12,0:16:00.46,ENG,,0,0,0,,The fraction of numbers that are not perfect squares
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.12,0:16:00.46,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.46,0:16:04.08,ENG,,0,0,0,,goes to one as X goes to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.46,0:16:04.08,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.08,0:16:07.58,ENG,,0,0,0,,And yet we know there are an infinite number of perfect squares
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.08,0:16:07.58,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.58,0:16:09.94,ENG,,0,0,0,,and we know exactly where they are.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.58,0:16:09.94,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.94,0:16:13.35,ENG,,0,0,0,,Now, we've tested by brute force all numbers up to 2^68,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.94,0:16:13.35,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.35,0:16:15.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,and they all obey the Collatz conjecture.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.35,0:16:15.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.54,0:16:19.87,ENG,,0,0,0,,And you might be thinking that we should have found a counterexample by this point.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.54,0:16:19.87,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.87,0:16:23.83,ENG,,0,0,0,,But on the scale of all numbers, 2^68 is nothing.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.87,0:16:23.83,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.83,0:16:27.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,I mean, the Pólya conjecture proposed in 1919 by George Pólya
Dialogue: 0,0:16:23.83,0:16:27.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.53,0:16:30.10,ENG,,0,0,0,,asserted that the majority of natural numbers
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.53,0:16:30.10,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.10,0:16:34.36,ENG,,0,0,0,,up to any given number have an odd number of prime factors.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:30.10,0:16:34.36,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.36,0:16:36.49,ENG,,0,0,0,,The conjecture was eventually proven false
Dialogue: 0,0:16:34.36,0:16:36.49,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.49,0:16:39.13,ENG,,0,0,0,,by C. Brian Haselgrove in 1958
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.49,0:16:39.13,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.13,0:16:41.61,ENG,,0,0,0,,when he identified a counterexample.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.13,0:16:41.61,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.61,0:16:44.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,What's remarkable is the value of this counterexample
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.61,0:16:44.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.27,0:16:48.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,was 1.845×10^361.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.27,0:16:48.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.01,0:16:50.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,That's some 10^340 times bigger
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.01,0:16:50.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.95,0:16:54.30,ENG,,0,0,0,,than all the numbers checked for 3x+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.95,0:16:54.30,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.30,0:16:55.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,One way to think about 3x+1
Dialogue: 0,0:16:54.30,0:16:55.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.90,0:16:59.73,ENG,,0,0,0,,is as though it's a simple program run on a Turing machine.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.90,0:16:59.73,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.73,0:17:03.22,ENG,,0,0,0,,The seed number is the input to the machine.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:59.73,0:17:03.22,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.22,0:17:08.68,ENG,,0,0,0,,So in this picture, 2^68 is simply an input tape 68 squares long.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.22,0:17:08.68,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.68,0:17:13.95,ENG,,0,0,0,,You can think of them as a string of ones and zeros or black and white squares.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:08.68,0:17:13.95,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.95,0:17:16.49,ENG,,0,0,0,,Saying the machine has transformed every input
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.95,0:17:16.49,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.49,0:17:19.54,ENG,,0,0,0,,up to this 68 square taped down to one
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.49,0:17:19.54,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.54,0:17:24.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,should not give you a lot of confidence that it will do so for all inputs.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:19.54,0:17:24.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.33,0:17:25.90,ENG,,0,0,0,,In fact, it's fairly simple
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.33,0:17:25.90,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.91,0:17:27.49,ENG,,0,0,0,,to calculate a number that shows
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.91,0:17:27.49,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.49,0:17:30.88,ENG,,0,0,0,,any arbitrary behavior you like, so long as it is finite.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:27.49,0:17:30.88,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.88,0:17:33.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,But if you want a number that increases by 3/2,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.88,0:17:33.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.33,0:17:36.37,ENG,,0,0,0,,five consecutive times, you can calculate that number.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.33,0:17:36.37,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.37,0:17:38.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,If you want a number that climbs by 3/2,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.37,0:17:38.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.27,0:17:39.80,ENG,,0,0,0,,10 times in a row, or
Dialogue: 0,0:17:38.27,0:17:39.80,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.80,0:17:41.98,ENG,,0,0,0,,100 times or 1,000 times,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:39.80,0:17:41.98,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.98,0:17:44.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,you can easily calculate those numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.98,0:17:44.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.53,0:17:46.81,ENG,,0,0,0,,But after the finite section you specify,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.53,0:17:46.81,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.81,0:17:48.46,ENG,,0,0,0,,you have no more control.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:46.81,0:17:48.46,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.46,0:17:52.69,ENG,,0,0,0,,And every that has ever been tested, always falls to one.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.46,0:17:52.69,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.69,0:17:57.65,ENG,,0,0,0,,If there is a counterexample, it's virtually impossible that someone's gonna guess it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.69,0:17:57.65,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.65,0:18:02.52,ENG,,0,0,0,,And the space of all possibilities is too big to search exhaustively by brute force.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:57.65,0:18:02.52,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.52,0:18:05.18,ENG,,0,0,0,,2^1,000 is not a searchable space.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.52,0:18:05.18,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.18,0:18:09.15,ENG,,0,0,0,,So, if we're gonna find it, we have to find it by some intelligent process
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.18,0:18:09.15,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.15,0:18:11.53,ENG,,0,0,0,,and not by guess and check.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:09.15,0:18:11.53,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.53,0:18:15.35,ENG,,0,0,0,,I had been on team 3x+1 for 20 years.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.53,0:18:15.35,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.35,0:18:18.68,ENG,,0,0,0,,And then this point of view,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.35,0:18:18.68,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.68,0:18:21.85,ENG,,0,0,0,,I realized that, what do we really know?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.68,0:18:21.85,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.40,0:18:25.75,ENG,,0,0,0,,It's very hard to prove a theorem that's false.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:23.40,0:18:25.75,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.47,0:18:29.51,ENG,,0,0,0,,And so, could it be that everyone is struggling
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.47,0:18:29.51,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.51,0:18:32.70,ENG,,0,0,0,,to prove this thing because it's not actually true?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.51,0:18:32.70,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.70,0:18:35.92,ENG,,0,0,0,,And 2^60 is not a lot of evidence.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.70,0:18:35.92,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.92,0:18:40.55,ENG,,0,0,0,,And even the statistical version is maybe true and
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.92,0:18:40.55,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.55,0:18:45.38,ENG,,0,0,0,,not evidence for the non-existence of a divergent trajectory somewhere
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.55,0:18:45.38,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.38,0:18:47.20,ENG,,0,0,0,,in the 3x+1 sequence.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.38,0:18:47.20,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.06,0:18:52.62,ENG,,0,0,0,,- Of course there is another option, and that is that we'll never know,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:48.06,0:18:52.62,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.62,0:18:55.13,ENG,,0,0,0,,that the problem is undecidable.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.62,0:18:55.13,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.13,0:19:00.13,ENG,,0,0,0,,In 1987, John Conway created a generalization of 3x+1.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.13,0:19:00.13,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.15,0:19:03.47,ENG,,0,0,0,,It was a mathematical machine that he called FRACTRAN.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.15,0:19:03.47,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.47,0:19:07.48,ENG,,0,0,0,,And he was able to show this machine is Turing-complete,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.47,0:19:07.48,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.48,0:19:11.26,ENG,,0,0,0,,which means it can do anything a modern computer can do,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.48,0:19:11.26,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.26,0:19:14.44,ENG,,0,0,0,,but it also means that it's subject to the halting problem,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.26,0:19:14.44,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.44,0:19:19.63,ENG,,0,0,0,,a chance that the machine never stops running and so doesn't give you an output.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:14.44,0:19:19.63,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.63,0:19:24.27,ENG,,0,0,0,,And this does not prove that 3x+1 is also subject to the halting problem,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:19.63,0:19:24.27,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:24.27,0:19:26.67,ENG,,0,0,0,,but it is possible that given what we know,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:24.27,0:19:26.67,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.67,0:19:31.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,we may never prove the Collatz conjecture true or false.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.67,0:19:31.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.01,0:19:33.51,ENG,,0,0,0,,- You're gonna be taught in school that we know a bunch of stuff
Dialogue: 0,0:19:31.01,0:19:33.51,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.51,0:19:36.48,ENG,,0,0,0,, and it's a lie. They're all lies.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.51,0:19:36.48,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.48,0:19:38.68,ENG,,0,0,0,,Here's this stupid little problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.48,0:19:38.68,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.68,0:19:43.14,ENG,,0,0,0,,Come on, really we can't solve this? Really?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.68,0:19:43.14,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.14,0:19:46.87,ENG,,0,0,0,,You know, it just shows that math is hard.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:43.14,0:19:46.87,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.87,0:19:51.01,ENG,,0,0,0,,If anything, it shows that all of the things that we can solve are miracles.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.87,0:19:51.01,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.01,0:19:54.74,ENG,,0,0,0,,We have no right to have solutions to all of these other problems.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.01,0:19:54.74,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.74,0:19:59.65,ENG,,0,0,0,,- For my whole life, I've thought of numbers as these incredibly regular things
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.74,0:19:59.65,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.65,0:20:02.78,ENG,,0,0,0,,full of patterns, symmetry, and repetition.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.65,0:20:02.78,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.78,0:20:07.33,ENG,,0,0,0,,But what I'm realizing only now is just how peculiar numbers really are.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:02.78,0:20:07.33,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.33,0:20:10.44,ENG,,0,0,0,,You can see this most clearly in the coral representation.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:07.33,0:20:10.44,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.44,0:20:12.74,ENG,,0,0,0,,From a simple mathematical operation
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.44,0:20:12.74,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.74,0:20:19.03,ENG,,0,0,0,,comes something intricate, organic-looking, and, thus far, intractable to us.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:12.74,0:20:19.03,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.03,0:20:21.52,ENG,,0,0,0,,Do all numbers connect to the structure?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.03,0:20:21.52,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.52,0:20:25.26,ENG,,0,0,0,,Or is there some unique filament, a spindly little thread,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:21.52,0:20:25.26,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.26,0:20:29.05,ENG,,0,0,0,,that doesn't connect to any of this, that runs off to infinity?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.26,0:20:29.05,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.05,0:20:31.76,ENG,,0,0,0,,And why is it so hard to tell?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.05,0:20:31.76,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.76,0:20:33.72,ENG,,0,0,0,,I think that's why Paul Erdős said,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:31.76,0:20:33.72,CHN,,0,0,0,,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.72,0:20:37.99,ENG,,0,0,0,,"Mathematics is not yet ripe enough for such questions."
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.72,0:20:37.99,CHN,,0,0,0,,
